{:proof/updated-at "2026-03-29T20:58:09.501151718Z", :proof/falsify-completed? true, :proof/cycles [{:cycle/id "apm-a01A04-C001", :cycle/blocker-id "root", :cycle/phase :completed, :cycle/phases-completed [:observe :propose :execute :validate :classify :integrate :commit :gate-review], :cycle/phase-data {:observe {:blocker-id "root", :notes "WHAT IS REALLY BEING ASKED: This is a three-part question about how the volume of the unit ball in R^n behaves as n grows. Part (a) asks you to find a recurrence: express the (n+1)-dimensional ball volume in terms of the n-dimensional one via an integral. Part (b) asks you to show the ratio of consecutive volumes goes to zero. Part (c) asks you to conclude that ball volume decays faster than any exponential — that is, A^n * vol(B_n) -> 0 for any constant A. The underlying phenomenon: high-dimensional unit balls have vanishingly small volume. Almost all the volume of the unit cube [-1,1]^n lies in the corners, not in the inscribed ball. WHY IT IS HARD: Part (a) requires knowing the Cavalieri slicing trick — express a higher-dimensional volume as an integral of lower-dimensional slices. Students who have not seen this before will not invent it under exam pressure. The function f turns out to be f(t) = sqrt(1-t^2), which is the radius of the cross-sectional ball at height t. Part (b) is a dominated convergence theorem application, but students must recognise that f(t) < 1 for all t except t=0 (a single point), so [f(t)]^n -> 0 a.e. Part (c) is a telescoping product argument: the ratio bound from (b) lets you dominate m(B_n) by a product of terms each less than 1/A, giving faster-than-geometric decay. Students who try to use an explicit volume formula (involving Gamma functions) are taking the hard road."}, :propose {:approach "Cavalieri slicing for (a), DCT for (b), telescoping product for (c).", :notes "THE KEY INSIGHT: Slice B_{n+1} perpendicular to the last coordinate axis at height t in [-1,1]. The slice is an n-dimensional ball of radius sqrt(1-t^2). By Fubini, the (n+1)-volume equals the integral of n-volumes of slices: m(B_{n+1}) = integral_{-1}^{1} m(B_{n,sqrt(1-t^2)}) dt = m(B_{n,1}) * integral [sqrt(1-t^2)]^n dt. So f(t) = sqrt(1-t^2) on [-1,1], zero elsewhere. This f maps R to [0,1] and satisfies [f(t)]^n = (1-t^2)^{n/2}. Part (b) then follows from DCT: [f(t)]^n -> 0 pointwise a.e. (since f(t)<1 for t != 0) and is bounded by chi_{[-1,1]}. Part (c) chains the ratio bound: once the ratio m(B_{n+1})/m(B_{n}) < 1/A for all large n, the volume decays geometrically with ratio < 1/A, so A^n times it still goes to zero. THE NAIVE APPROACH THAT FAILS: Try to compute m(B_{n,1}) explicitly using the Gamma function formula: m(B_{n,1}) = pi^{n/2} / Gamma(n/2 + 1). Then try Stirling's approximation to show A^n * pi^{n/2} / Gamma(n/2+1) -> 0. This works but is much harder than the slicing approach — you need detailed Stirling asymptotics, and the exam is testing Fubini + DCT, not special functions. The slicing approach uses only tools from the Lp/measure theory syllabus."}, :execute {:artifacts ["proof-a01A04-inline" "lean-proofs/a01A04"], :notes "THE CLEAN PROOF:\n\nPart (a). Define f: R -> [0,1] by f(t) = sqrt(1 - t^2) for |t| <= 1, and f(t) = 0 for |t| > 1. We claim m(B_{n+1,1}) = m(B_{n,1}) * integral [f(t)]^n dt.\n\nSlice B_{n+1,1} by the hyperplane x_{n+1} = t. For a point (x_1,...,x_{n+1}) in B_{n+1,1}, we need x_1^2 + ... + x_{n+1}^2 <= 1, which at height x_{n+1} = t means x_1^2 + ... + x_n^2 <= 1 - t^2. This is exactly the n-ball of radius sqrt(1 - t^2). The slice exists only for |t| <= 1.\n\nBy Fubini's theorem:\n  m(B_{n+1,1}) = integral_{-1}^{1} m(B_{n, sqrt(1-t^2)}) dt\n\nThe volume of an n-ball of radius r is r^n * m(B_{n,1}) (scaling property of Lebesgue measure). So m(B_{n, sqrt(1-t^2)}) = (sqrt(1-t^2))^n * m(B_{n,1}) = [f(t)]^n * m(B_{n,1}).\n\nSubstituting:\n  m(B_{n+1,1}) = integral_{-1}^{1} [f(t)]^n * m(B_{n,1}) dt = m(B_{n,1}) * integral_{-1}^{1} [f(t)]^n dt\n\nSince f(t) = 0 for |t| > 1, the integral over R equals the integral over [-1,1]:\n  m(B_{n+1,1}) = m(B_{n,1}) * integral_R [f(t)]^n dt.  QED for (a).\n\nPart (b). We show integral [f(t)]^n dt -> 0 as n -> infinity.\n\nPointwise: for t != 0 with |t| <= 1, we have 0 <= f(t) = sqrt(1-t^2) < 1, so [f(t)]^n -> 0 as n -> infinity. At t = 0, f(0) = 1, so [f(0)]^n = 1 for all n. For |t| > 1, [f(t)]^n = 0. Thus [f(t)]^n -> 0 for a.e. t (the exception {0} has Lebesgue measure zero).\n\nDomination: |[f(t)]^n| <= 1 * chi_{[-1,1]}(t) for all n, and chi_{[-1,1]} is in L^1 (it integrates to 2).\n\nBy the Dominated Convergence Theorem: integral [f(t)]^n dt -> integral 0 dt = 0. QED for (b).\n\nPart (c). Fix A > 0. We show A^n * m(B_{n,1}) -> 0.\n\nBy parts (a) and (b), the ratio r_n := m(B_{n+1,1}) / m(B_{n,1}) = integral [f(t)]^n dt -> 0 as n -> infinity.\n\nChoose N such that for all n >= N, r_n < 1/(2A). (This is possible since r_n -> 0.)\n\nFor n > N, telescope:\n  m(B_{n,1}) = m(B_{N,1}) * product_{k=N}^{n-1} r_k <= m(B_{N,1}) * (1/(2A))^{n-N}\n\nTherefore:\n  A^n * m(B_{n,1}) <= A^n * m(B_{N,1}) * (1/(2A))^{n-N}\n                    = m(B_{N,1}) * (2A)^N * (A / (2A))^n\n                    = m(B_{N,1}) * (2A)^N * (1/2)^n -> 0.\n\nSince (1/2)^n -> 0, we conclude A^n * m(B_{n,1}) -> 0. QED for (c)."}, :validate {:validation-artifacts ["lean-proofs/a01A04/Main.lean"], :notes "NON-CIRCULARITY ANALYSIS: The proof composes four independent facts:\n(i) Fubini/Cavalieri: the (n+1)-volume equals the integral of n-volume slices. This is a general measure-theoretic fact, independent of the specific integrand.\n(ii) Scaling property: m(B_{n,r}) = r^n * m(B_{n,1}). This is a property of Lebesgue measure under dilation, independent of the slicing.\n(iii) DCT: pointwise a.e. convergence + domination implies integral convergence. This is pure measure theory.\n(iv) Telescoping product: if ratios r_n -> 0, the product decays super-exponentially. This is pure real analysis.\nNone of these facts references the others. The proof chains them: (i)+(ii) give the recurrence, (iii) gives part (b), (iv) uses (b) for part (c). The Lean formalization closes: definition of ballSliceRadius, nonnegativity, upper bound (le_one), strict inequality (lt_one for t != 0), and pointwise power convergence to zero. All zero sorry. What remains un-formalized: the integral formulation (Fubini slicing + DCT integral convergence + telescoping product argument). These would require Fubini-Tonelli for the slicing and MeasureTheory.tendsto_integral_of_dominated_convergence for the DCT step."}, :classify {:classification :partial, :rationale "Informal proof complete for all three parts. Lean formalization: 5 lemmas closed (zero sorry) covering the core real-analysis component (f definition, bounds, strict bound, pointwise convergence). The integral-level statements (Fubini slicing, DCT integral convergence, telescoping product) remain un-formalized — these need MeasureTheory.tendsto_integral_of_dominated_convergence and Fubini-Tonelli API wiring which exceeded the time budget.", :notes "CONFIDENCE INVERSION: The surprise is that the unit ball in R^n has vanishing volume as n grows. Intuition says bigger space = more room, so the ball should get bigger. The truth: the ball occupies a vanishing fraction of the cube [-1,1]^n. By part (c), ball volume decays faster than ANY exponential A^{-n}. A concrete shock: in R^{100}, the unit ball has volume roughly 10^{-40} — the inscribed ball is a negligible speck inside the unit cube. This is why high-dimensional probability concentrates on thin shells, not ball interiors. The curse of dimensionality is not a metaphor — it is the content of part (c)."}, :integrate {:rationale "Three-part proof complete with partial Lean formalization.", :ledger-changes [], :notes "CONNECTIONS: The vanishing of ball volume connects to: (1) Concentration of measure phenomenon — high-dimensional uniform distributions concentrate on thin shells near the boundary. (2) Curse of dimensionality in machine learning — volume-based methods (kNN, kernel density) degrade in high dimensions because nearly all volume is in corners. (3) The explicit formula m(B_n) = pi^{n/2}/Gamma(n/2+1) via Stirling shows the super-exponential decay directly, but the slicing approach is more elegant and generalizable. (4) Gaussian annulus theorem: a Gaussian in R^n concentrates in a thin shell at radius sqrt(n), which is the probabilistic cousin of this volume decay.\n\nEXAM-DAY FIELD KIT: (1) Cavalieri/Fubini slicing: m(B_{n+1}) = integral of m(slice at height t) dt. (2) Scaling: m(B_{n,r}) = r^n m(B_{n,1}). (3) The function f(t) = sqrt(1-t^2) gives [f(t)]^n -> 0 a.e. with integrable dominator chi_{[-1,1]}. (4) DCT for the integral convergence. (5) Telescoping: if ratio -> 0, product decays faster than any geometric sequence. These five facts compose cleanly — learn them as a unit."}, :commit {:saved? true}, :gate-review {:gates-passed true, :result-status :partial}}, :cycle/started-at "2026-03-29T20:58:20.171838070Z", :cycle/updated-at "2026-03-29T21:03:19.703408801Z", :cycle/result-status :partial}], :proof/ledger {"part-a" {:item/id "part-a", :item/label "(a) Show that $\\exists f:\\R\\rightarrow [0,1]$ such that\n$m\\{B_{n", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{}, :item/unlocks #{"part-b"}, :item/evidence-type :analytical}, "part-b" {:item/id "part-b", :item/label "(b) Show that $\\int[f(t)]^n dt\\rightarrow 0$ as $n\\rightarrow\n\\i", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{"part-a"}, :item/unlocks #{"part-c"}, :item/evidence-type :analytical}, "part-c" {:item/id "part-c", :item/label "(c) Show that for any finite positive number $A$, $A^n\nm\\{B_{n,1", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{"part-b"}, :item/unlocks #{"root"}, :item/evidence-type :analytical}, "root" {:item/id "root", :item/label "Complete proof of a01A04", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{"part-c"}, :item/unlocks #{}, :item/evidence-type :analytical}}, :proof/active-license nil, :proof/current-mode :CONSTRUCT, :proof/problem-id "apm-a01A04", :proof/canonical {:statement "Let $B_{m,1}$ denote the ball of radius $1$ centered at the origin in\n$\\Rm$.\n%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%\n\\begin{alist}\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\item Show that $\\exists f:\\R\\rightarrow [0,1]$ such that\n$m\\{B_{n+1,1}\\}=m\\{B_{n,1}\\}\\int [f(t)]^n dt$.\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\item Show that $\\int[f(t)]^n dt\\rightarrow 0$ as $n\\rightarrow\n\\infty$.\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\item Show that for any finite positive number $A$, $A^n\nm\\{B_{n,1}\\}\\rightarrow 0$ as $n\\rightarrow \\infty$.\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\end{alist}\n%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%\n\n", :closure-criterion "All parts proved analytically", :statement-hash "11ef1e2e616f19b77c4dfb3275f2d6069f8567605129da193832cd4dc7c0ffab", :version-history [{:version 0, :statement "Let $B_{m,1}$ denote the ball of radius $1$ centered at the origin in\n$\\Rm$.\n%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%\n\\begin{alist}\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\item Show that $\\exists f:\\R\\rightarrow [0,1]$ such that\n$m\\{B_{n+1,1}\\}=m\\{B_{n,1}\\}\\int [f(t)]^n dt$.\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\item Show that $\\int[f(t)]^n dt\\rightarrow 0$ as $n\\rightarrow\n\\infty$.\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\item Show that for any finite positive number $A$, $A^n\nm\\{B_{n,1}\\}\\rightarrow 0$ as $n\\rightarrow \\infty$.\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\end{alist}\n%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%\n\n", :hash "11ef1e2e616f19b77c4dfb3275f2d6069f